Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. records.addlTxt: 10:14 AM Defendant Phillip Joseph Whiteman in court with attorney Eric P Habich.  Alexander Paul Seifert appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Attorney Habich appears remotely, did file a request to appear remotely but no Order was attached, reminds him to do that. Habich understands that. Whiteman and Habich have complaint, waives reading of it, have filed a Waiver of Right to PH. Court has waiver of PH form, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his right to PH, finds probable cause, bind over for trial. State has not filed Information yet but will forthwith. Habich will proceed to ARGN and stands mute. State will file an  Information that mirrors the complaint. Habich enters NG pleas to all counts. Court accepts plea, continues bond, set for JT, if resolved - contact JA for PLEAS.
